<i>Mount Sharp is three miles high
 of layered sediment.</i>

00:01:05.431 --> 00:01:08.701
The kinds of outcrops of rock
that we've been looking at

00:01:08.701 --> 00:01:11.971
since we landed are more like
ankle and knee high.

00:01:11.971 --> 00:01:14.573
And some of them
are down underfoot like

00:01:14.573 --> 00:01:16.008
the mudstone that we drill.

00:01:16.008 --> 00:01:18.144
By the way,
two years ago when we landed,

00:01:18.144 --> 00:01:19.645
if you said the first thing
we drilled

00:01:19.645 --> 00:01:21.580
was going to be a mudstone.

00:01:21.580 --> 00:01:23.316
And that,
we would find that it was

00:01:23.316 --> 00:01:25.317
actually
habitable environment,

00:01:25.317 --> 00:01:26.585
I wouldn't have believed you.

00:01:26.585 --> 00:01:29.689
So, this has been
an amazing two years.

00:01:29.689 --> 00:01:32.625
<i> You see, Curiosity carries
 its name on its arm,</i>

00:01:32.625 --> 00:01:35.228
<i> it carries its name
 on its sleeve.</i>

00:01:35.228 --> 00:01:38.063
And... what we are doing,

00:01:38.063 --> 00:01:40.166
we are geologists
for the most part,

00:01:40.166 --> 00:01:42.702
and what we are doing is,
trying to read the history

00:01:42.702 --> 00:01:45.104
of this place
in the layered rock.

00:01:45.104 --> 00:01:47.106
We call it stratigraphy.

00:01:47.106 --> 00:01:51.277
So basically, the oldest rocks
are at the bottom of the stack

00:01:51.277 --> 00:01:52.945
and the youngest
are at the top,

00:01:52.945 --> 00:01:54.147
and so, if you go like,

00:01:54.147 --> 00:01:55.748
to the Grand Canyon
in Arizona,

00:01:55.748 --> 00:02:00.153
for example or Letchworth,
I've been there many times.

00:02:00.153 --> 00:02:02.788
Older... younger.
So, what you see

00:02:02.788 --> 00:02:05.491
<i> here behind me is one of these
 landscapes in a place</i>

